                            <td colspan="2" class="redHead"><b>Important Points</b></td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr> 
                            <td>&nbsp;</td>
                            <td> 
                              <ol>
                                <li>Remember that a letter asking for a job is 
                                  a sales letter, you are selling yourself and your skills. It also serves as an introduction 
                                  or &quot;first impression.&quot;</li>
                                <li>It is a good idea to go over the letter to 
                                  check for clarity and correctness in spelling 
                                  and grammar.</li>
                                <li>Keep the language simple and friendly. Be 
                                  your own natural self. <b>AVOID </b>appearing 
                                  aggressive, familiar, or humorous.</li>
                                <li>Keep the letter short. In fact, avoid covering 
                                  the same material as in your accompanying resume.</li>
                                <li>Use plain white, standard business-size stationary. No 10 lb. fancy paper stock is required- you are not trying to sell the paper!</li>
                                <li>Angle the letter toward what you can offer 
                                  an employer, not what you think the employer 
                                  should be offering you. Emphasize as much as possible how your skills 
                                  and attitude relate to the particular position 
                                  for which you are applying.</li>
